{"id":"2110.10155","submitter":"Sergey Chefranov","authors":"Sergey G. Chefranov, Yakov E. Krasik, and Alexander Rososhek","title":"Limitation in velocity of converging shock wave","comments":"4 figures","journal-ref":"Phys.Fluids,34, 016101 (2022)","doi":"10.1063/5.0076353","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.flu-dyn","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The commonly applied self-similar solution of the problem of the converging\nshock wave (shock) evolution with constant compression of the medium behind the\nshock front results in an unlimited increase of the medium velocity in the\nvicinity of the implosion. In this paper, the convergence of cylindrical shocks\nin water is analyzed using the mass conservation law, when the water\ncompression behind the shock front is a variable. The model predicts a finite\nrange of radii, which depends on the adiabatic index of water and where the\nincrease in pressure exceeds the sum of the change of the kinetic and internal\nenergy densities behind the shock front. In this range of radii only the finite\nincrease of the shock and water flow velocities is realized.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 19 Oct 2021 13:12:58 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sat, 12 Feb 2022 13:34:43 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-02-15"}
